---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What to Do After Your AuDHD Quiz"
  description="You took an AuDHD quiz. Now what? What your results mean, whether self-identification is valid, and practical next steps for either outcome."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">What to Do After Your AuDHD Quiz</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        You took the quiz. Maybe you scored high. Maybe the results were mixed. Either way, you're probably sitting with a mix of recognition, confusion, and "okay but what do I actually do now?" This page is for that exact moment.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">What Your Quiz Results Actually Mean</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          First, the honest truth: no online quiz can diagnose AuDHD. Not ours, not anyone's. What a good quiz can do is help you <strong class="text-text">organize your experiences</strong> and identify patterns worth investigating further. Think of it as a starting point for a conversation, not the final word.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          A high score means your reported experiences align with common AuDHD patterns. It doesn't guarantee a diagnosis, because other conditions can share overlapping traits. Anxiety, PTSD, giftedness, and sensory processing differences can all mimic aspects of AuDHD. A low score doesn't rule it out either, especially if you've been masking for decades and have learned to compensate so well that even your self-report doesn't fully capture what's happening underneath.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          The most useful thing you can do with your results? Use them as a reference document. Print them or save them. Bring them to a professional if you pursue assessment. "Here's what I noticed about myself" is more productive than trying to remember everything in a clinical appointment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Is Self-Identification Valid?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Yes. And this is a hill many neurodivergent communities will die on, for good reason. Formal diagnosis is gatekept by cost, geography, provider availability, racial and gender bias in diagnostic criteria, and waitlists that stretch for years. Requiring a formal diagnosis before someone can access community, resources, or self-understanding excludes the people who need it most.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Self-identification doesn't mean reading one article and deciding you're AuDHD. It means sustained pattern recognition over time. Reading about autistic and ADHD experiences and repeatedly thinking "that's exactly my experience." Recognizing yourself in the <a href="/learn/signs-of-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">signs and traits</a> in a way that goes beyond casual relatability. Understanding not just the surface behaviors but the underlying reasons (sensory differences, executive function, social processing) that drive them.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          That said, formal assessment has practical benefits. Workplace accommodations, disability support, medication access, and (for some people) the psychological weight of official validation. Self-identification and formal diagnosis aren't opposing paths. Many people self-identify first and pursue assessment later when it makes sense for their situation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">If Your Score Was High</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Take a breath. Whatever you're feeling right now is normal. Relief, anxiety, "I've known this for years," or "this changes everything" are all common responses. There's no wrong way to react to information about your own brain.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Practical next steps:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li><strong class="text-text">Learn more about the specific areas where you scored highest.</strong> Understanding your own patterns is immediately useful, with or without a formal diagnosis. Our pages on <a href="/learn/audhd-vs-adhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD vs ADHD</a> and <a href="/learn/audhd-vs-autism/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD vs autism</a> can help you untangle which traits come from which condition.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Start implementing accommodations now.</strong> You don't need a diagnosis to buy noise-canceling headphones, adjust your schedule, or be more intentional about sensory management. Small changes often produce surprisingly big results.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Consider formal assessment</strong> if you want medication, workplace accommodations, or the certainty that a clinical evaluation provides. Our <a href="/learn/getting-assessed/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">assessment guide</a> walks through the whole process.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Check in on burnout.</strong> Many people discover AuDHD when they're already running on fumes. If that's you, the <a href="/quiz/audhd-burnout/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">burnout quiz</a> is worth taking.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">If Your Score Was Low or Mixed</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          A lower score doesn't necessarily mean "not AuDHD." It might mean you're masking heavily enough that your self-report underestimates your actual experience. It might mean your specific trait profile doesn't align with the quiz's question set. Or it might genuinely mean that your experiences are better explained by something else.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          If the quiz didn't resonate but you still feel like something is going on, keep exploring. Look into sensory processing differences, anxiety disorders, PTSD (which overlaps significantly with both autism and ADHD presentations), or giftedness. The goal isn't a specific label. The goal is understanding yourself well enough to get the right support.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Resources That Actually Help</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Books like <em>Unmasking Autism</em> by Devon Price and <em>Scattered Minds</em> by Gabor Mate have been pivotal for many adults exploring neurodivergence. For AuDHD specifically, community resources often outpace published research, because the formal recognition of this dual diagnosis is still relatively recent.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Whatever your results showed, the fact that you took the quiz means you noticed something about yourself worth investigating. That awareness matters. Where you go from here is your choice, and there's no rush.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Take the AuDHD Quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/getting-assessed/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">How to get assessed for AuDHD &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/signs-of-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Signs of AuDHD &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
